Project Summary


From heat mapping to cooling-priority screening


Problem Statement


Extreme heat is an increasing planning concern for London, but heat exposure is spatially uneven. Dense built-up areas with limited vegetation and poorer access to cool spaces may experience higher cooling needs than greener neighbourhoods under the same city-wide heat warning. The application answers one practical question: where should cooling interventions be prioritised?


End User


The tool is designed for London borough officers, climate adaptation teams, urban greening practitioners and community-facing planners. It does not replace detailed thermal-comfort modelling; instead, it provides a transparent neighbourhood-scale screening tool for comparing heat burden, cooling capacity, population exposure and cool-space access.




Planning Context


Policy background


The project is framed by The London Plan 2021, especially policies on managing heat risk, urban greening and fair access to climate adaptation resources.


&lt;article class="info-card accent-orange"&gt;
  &lt;h3&gt;The London Plan 2021 · Policy SI 4&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;h4&gt;Managing Heat Risk&lt;/h4&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Policy SI 4 treats overheating as a planning issue. In this project, land surface temperature is used to identify areas with stronger summer heat burden and to support spatial cooling priorities.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;
&lt;article class="info-card accent-green"&gt;
  &lt;h3&gt;The London Plan 2021 · Policy G5&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;h4&gt;Urban Greening&lt;/h4&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Policy G5 highlights urban greening as part of development and climate adaptation. NDVI is used here as a remote-sensing indicator of vegetation-related cooling potential.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;
&lt;article class="info-card accent-blue"&gt;
  &lt;h3&gt;Good Growth and Access&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;h4&gt;Cooling as an equity issue&lt;/h4&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Population density and cool-space accessibility help show where cooling resources may not align with local need, turning the project from a heat map into a planning-support tool.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;




