&lt;div class="flow-arrow"&gt;→&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="flow-node process"&gt;Equal weight&lt;span&gt;1/3 each&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="flow-arrow"&gt;→&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="flow-node score"&gt;Cooling Condition Score&lt;span&gt;LST + NDVI + NDBI&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;div class="flow-note"&gt;Planning interpretation layers&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="flow-arrow"&gt;→&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="flow-right"&gt;
  &lt;div class="flow-node purple"&gt;Population&lt;span&gt;exposure layer&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="flow-node blue"&gt;Accessibility&lt;span&gt;cool-space access&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="flow-arrow"&gt;→&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="flow-node output"&gt;Priority Areas&lt;span&gt;planning interpretation&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


The Cooling Condition Score is therefore an environmental composite index. Population and accessibility are not used to calculate the score itself; they help interpret where relatively poor cooling conditions may affect more residents or coincide with weaker access to cooling resources.
The final score is then aggregated to LSOA level for comparison and interactive mapping. Higher values indicate relatively warmer or less favourable cooling conditions, while lower values indicate relatively cooler or more favourable conditions.
